ant of   Ovington  , which, like <i>Howington</i>, is recorded in North Yorkshire in the 17th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ovington","meanings":["English (Durham):","habitational name from Ovington (Durham). The placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wulfa</i> + connective <i>-ing-</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’.","possibly a variant of <b>Ovenden</b>, a habitational name perhaps derived from Ovingdean (Sussex) or Ovenden (Yorkshire). The placename Ovingdean derives from the Old English personal name <i>Ofa</i> or <i>Ūfa</i> + the Old English group name suffix <i>-ingas</i> (genitive <i>-inga-</i>) + Old English <i>denu</i> ‘valley’. The placename Ovenden derives from Old English <i>ofen</i> ‘furnace’ or <i>ofan</i>, <i>ufan</i> ‘over, above’ + <i>denu</i> ‘valley’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":14,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":87,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Hodington was born in 1368, in Huddington, Worcestershire, England. He had at least 2 daughters with Joan Thurgrim."},"et":{"1368–":"1368–Surnud","1372–Female":"1372–Surnud","1395–Female":"1395–Surnud","1396–Female":"1396–Surnud","1368–Male":"1368–Surnud","1368":"1368","1455":"1455","1396":"1396","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","Huddington, Worcestershire, England":"Huddington, Worcestershire, England"},"fi":{"1368–":"1368–Kuollut","1372–Female":"1372–Kuollut","1395–Female":"1395–Kuollut","1396–Female":"1396–Kuollut","1368–Male":"1368–Kuollut","1368":"1368","1455":"1455","1396":"1396","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","Huddington, Worcestershire, England":"Huddington, Worcestershire, England"},"fr":{"1368–":"1368–Décédé","1372–Female":"1372–Décédée","1395–Female":"1395–Décédée","1396–Female":"1396–Décédée","1368–Male":"1368–Décédé","1368":"1368","1455":"1455","1396":"1396","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","Huddington, Worcestershire, England":"Huddington, Worcestershire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Thomas Hodington est né en 1368, à Huddington, Worcestershire, Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 2 filles avec Joan Thurgrim."},"de":{"1368–":"1368–Verstorben","1372–Female":"1372–Verstorben","1395–Female":"1395–Verstorben","1396–Female":"1396–Verstorben","1368–Male":"1368–Verstorben","1368":"1368","1455":"1455","1396":"1396","1395":"1395","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","Huddington, Worcestershire, England":"Huddington, Worcestershire, England","lifeSummary":"Thomas Hodington wurde 1368 in Huddington, Worcestershire, England geboren. Er hatte mit Joan Thurgrim mindestens 2 Töch